{"title_page": "Who Killed Vincent Chin?", "text_new": "{{short description|1987 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Who Killed Vincent Chin?\n| image          =\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[Christine Choy]]<br>[[Renee Tajima-Pe\u00f1a]]\n| producer       = Christine Choy<br>Renee Tajima-Pe\u00f1a\n| writer         =\n| narrator       =\n| starring       =\n| music          =\n| cinematography = Kyle Kibbe\n| editing        = Holly Fisher\n| studio         = [[Third World Newsreel|Film News Now Foundation]] and [[WTVS]]\n| distributor    = [[Filmakers Library]]\n| released       = {{film date|1987}}\n| runtime        = 87 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English<br />Cantonese\n}}\n'''''Who Killed Vincent Chin?''''' is a 1987 American [[documentary film]] directed by [[Christine Choy]] and [[Renee Tajima-Pe\u00f1a]] that recounts the [[murder of Vincent Chin]]. It was nominated for an [[Academy Award]] for [[Academy Award for Best Documentary Feature|Best Documentary Feature]].<ref name=\"Oscars\">{{cite web|title=THE 61ST ACADEMY AWARDS (1989)|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1989|website=Oscars.org|publisher=The Academy Awards|accessdate=September 2, 2015}}</ref> It was later broadcast as part of the [[PBS]] series ''[[POV (TV series)|POV]]''.\n\n==Synopsis==\nOn a summer night in Detroit, two white unemployed autoworkers fatally beat Vincent Chin, a 27-year-old Chinese engineer, with a baseball bat.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Xing|first1=Jun|title=Asian America Through the Lens|date=1998|publisher=AltaMira Press|location=CA|isbn=9780761991762|page=109}}</ref> The film tracks the incident from the initial eye-witness accounts through the trial and its repercussions for the families involved, and the American justice system at large.<ref>{{cite book|title=Who Killed Vincent Chin?|url=https://www.pbs.org/pov/whokilledvincentchin/| publisher=PBS|accessdate=September 3, 2015|date=1987}}</ref> After an outcry from the Asian American community, led by Vincent's mother Lily Chin, the case becomes a [[civil rights]] Supreme Court case. The case ends with tried killer [[Ronald Ebens]]' being let go with a suspended sentence and a small fine.<ref>{{cite book|title=Who Killed Vincent Chin? |url=http://www.filmakers.com/indivs/WhoVincentChin.htm ||publisher=Filmmakers Library at filmmakers.com|accessdate=September 3, 2015 |date=1987|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061020032732/http://www.filmakers.com/indivs/WhoVincentChin.htm |archivedate=October 20, 2006 }}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n*[[Alfred I. duPont\u2013Columbia University Award]], Silver Baton (1991)<ref>{{cite web|title=All duPont-Columbia Award Winners|url=http://www.journalism.columbia.edu/page/412-past-dupont-award-winners/594|website=Columbia Journalism School|accessdate=September 2, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120814182043/http://www.journalism.columbia.edu/page/412-past-dupont-award-winners/594#|archive-date=August 14, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*Hawaii International Film Festival, Best Documentary Award (1988)<ref>{{cite web|title=8th Annual Hawaii International Film Festival|url=http://www.hiff.org/about-hiff/history/hiff-1988/|website=Hawaii International Film Festival|accessdate=September 2, 2015}}</ref> \n*Academy Awards, Best Documentary Feature Nominee (1989)<ref name=\"Oscars\"/>\n\n==See also==\n''[[Vincent Who?]]'', 2009 documentary about the same case.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Imdb title|id=0096440|title=Who Killed Vincent Chin?}}\n*[https://www.pbs.org/pov/whokilledvincentchin/ ''Who Killed Vincent Chin?''] at ''[[POV (TV series)|POV]]''\n*[https://search.alexanderstreet.com/preview/work/bibliographic_entity%7Cvideo_work%7C1785304 ''Who Killed Vincent Chin?''] at [[Filmakers Library]]\n\n[[Category:1987 films]]\n[[Category:1980s documentary films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American documentary films]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about Asian Americans]]\n[[Category:Chinese-American films]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about racism in the United States]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Mandarin-language films]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about Detroit]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about the automotive industry]]\n[[Category:Films set in Detroit]]\n[[Category:Culture of Detroit]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1987 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Who Killed Vincent Chin?\n| image          =\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[Christine Choy]]<br>[[Renee Tajima-Pe\u00f1a]]\n| producer       = Christine Choy<br>Renee Tajima-Pe\u00f1a\n| writer         =\n| narrator       =\n| starring       =\n| music          =\n| cinematography = Kyle Kibbe\n| editing        = Holly Fisher\n| studio         = [[Third World Newsreel|Film News Now Foundation]] and [[WTVS]]\n| distributor    = [[Filmakers Library]]\n| released       = {{film date|1987}}\n| runtime        = 87 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English<br />Cantonese\n}}\n'''''Who Killed Vincent Chin?''''' is a 1987 American [[documentary film]] directed by [[Christine Choy]] and [[Renee Tajima-Pe\u00f1a]] that recounts the [[murder of Vincent Chin]]. It was nominated for an [[Academy Award]] for [[Academy Award for Best Documentary Feature|Best Documentary Feature]].<ref name=\"Oscars\">{{cite web|title=THE 61ST ACADEMY AWARDS (1989)|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1989|website=Oscars.org|publisher=The Academy Awards|accessdate=September 2, 2015}}</ref> It was later broadcast as part of the [[PBS]] series ''[[POV (TV series)|POV]]''.\n\n==Synopsis==\nOn a summer night in Detroit, two white unemployed autoworkers fatally beat Vincent Chin, a 27-year-old Chinese engineer, with a baseball bat.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Xing|first1=Jun|title=Asian America Through the Lens|date=1998|pu